                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3dz03j37/manifest/annotation/p2",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>time when so little of the genuine spirit of our religion appears\n                                        to<lb/> prevail, it is to be apprehended that intrigue,\n                                        selfishness and<lb/> vanity may have more to do with the\n                                        appointments of Delegates<lb/> than truly religious motives,\n                                        unworthy means the sincerely<lb/> devoted man will scorn to\n                                        employ, and unworthy motives will<lb/> not\n                                                  activate<add>?</add> him on such an occasion. He\n                                        would on the contrary<lb/> be apt to keep aloof that his\n                                        motives might not misconstrued.</p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(1)\">After this, Reverend Sir; and allow such men an\n                                        opportunity<lb/> to come forward voluntarily and\n                                        independently to serve their people<lb/> and the cause:—if\n                                        you do not I predict the affair will prove<lb/> a failure at\n                                        the very out set. I learned with concern that you<lb/> had\n                                        been several days confined to your room by\n                                        indisposition—<lb/> but was glad to find by my son's report\n                                        that you were better.</p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(1)\">To your indisposition and incessant labours I\n                                        ascribe my not<lb/> having <add>?</add> favored with alive\n                                        in acknowledgment of my<lb/> several late letters &amp;c. I\n                                        pray that, if you can spare time for no<lb/> more, you will\n                                        write me a few lines on the subject of the 50 copies<lb/> of\n                                        my letters—I am employed on the 5<hi rend=\"sup\">th</hi> with\n                                        which I shall<lb/> conclude the exposition of the Divine\n                                        Plan for the Government<lb/> of man, and may then return to\n                                        the other points connected with<lb/> the Union of the\n                                        Congregations as I situated my intention to touch<lb/> upon.\n                                        My letters 3, 4, &amp; 5 will have conducted the\n                                        exposition<lb/> to the period of the sentences passed on the\n                                        first pair and then<lb/> deceiver, which will disclose fully\n                                        the principles upon which<lb/> the divine economy is based.\n                                        All that follow, in the Bible,</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3dz03j37/canvas/p2"
                }
              ]
